=========================================
C++ PRIORITY_QUEUE
INTERVIEW PREPARATION NOTES
=========================================

1. What is priority_queue?
--------------------------

priority_queue is an STL container adaptor that stores elements based on priority rather than insertion order.

Default behavior:
Largest element has highest priority.

Example:

priority_queue<int> pq;

pq.push(10);
pq.push(30);
pq.push(20);

pq.top();   // 30

Interview Answer:
priority_queue is a heap-based container adaptor where the highest-priority element is always available at the top.

-----------------------------------------

2. Difference between queue and priority_queue?
-----------------------------------------------

queue
------
FIFO (First In First Out)

10 -> 20 -> 30

pop() => 10

priority_queue
--------------
Highest priority element removed first

10, 30, 20

pop() => 30

Interview Answer:
queue processes elements in insertion order, while priority_queue processes elements according to priority.

-----------------------------------------

3. How is priority_queue implemented internally?
------------------------------------------------

Implemented using a Heap.

Default:
Max Heap

Underlying container:
vector

Visual:

        50
       /  \
     30    40
    / \
   10 20

Largest element stays at root.

Interview Answer:
priority_queue is implemented using a heap (typically a binary heap) stored internally in a vector.

-----------------------------------------

4. What is a Heap?
------------------

Heap is a Complete Binary Tree that satisfies the heap property.

Max Heap:
---------
Parent >= Children

        50
       /  \
     30    40
    / \
   10 20

Min Heap:
---------
Parent <= Children

        10
       /  \
     20    30
    / \
   40 50

-----------------------------------------

5. Why is top() O(1)?
---------------------

The highest-priority element is always stored at the root.

Example:

        50
       /  \
     30    40

top() simply returns root.

Complexity:

O(1)

-----------------------------------------

6. Complexity
-------------

top()         O(1)
push()        O(log n)
pop()         O(log n)
empty()       O(1)
size()        O(1)

-----------------------------------------

7. Default Heap Type?
---------------------

Max Heap

Example:

priority_queue<int> pq;

pq.push(10);
pq.push(30);
pq.push(20);

pq.top();   // 30

Largest element appears first.

-----------------------------------------

8. How do you create a Min Heap?
--------------------------------

priority_queue<
    int,
    vector<int>,
    greater<int>
> pq;

Example:

pq.push(30);
pq.push(10);
pq.push(20);

pq.top();   // 10

-----------------------------------------

9. Why is priority_queue a container adaptor?
---------------------------------------------

Because it is built on top of another STL container.

Default:

vector

Similar to:

stack
queue

Interview Answer:
priority_queue adapts another container and provides heap behavior instead of exposing all container operations.

-----------------------------------------

10. Default underlying container?
---------------------------------

vector

Example:

priority_queue<
    int,
    vector<int>
> pq;

-----------------------------------------

11. Why can't priority_queue be iterated?
-----------------------------------------

priority_queue intentionally hides the internal heap structure.

Allowed operations:

push()
pop()
top()

Interview Answer:
priority_queue exposes only the highest-priority element and hides the internal heap implementation.

-----------------------------------------

